OPTION A — MATLAB (recommended if your lab has MATLAB)
Step-by-step (GUI quick method)

Open MATLAB. Type fuzzy in command window → opens Fuzzy Logic Designer (GUI).

In the GUI: File → New Mamdani FIS (or newfis in code).

Add input variable(s): set universe (e.g., temperature 0–100). Add MFs (trimf/trapmf/gaussmf).

Add output variable: set universe and MFs (e.g., fan speed low/med/high).

Click Rules → add IF–THEN rules (use AND/OR). Example: IF temp IS high AND humidity IS low THEN fan IS fast.

Use Rule viewer and Surface viewer to visualize firing strengths and output surface.

Use Defuzzification method (centroid) — check result on Rule Viewer (shows crisp output).

Save the FIS file (.fis) and export rules/plots for your report.

Short MATLAB script (non-GUI; create same FIS programmatically)
% create Mamdani FIS
fis = newfis('fanControl','mamdani');

% add inputs
fis = addvar(fis,'input','temperature',[0 100]);
fis = addmf(fis,'input',1,'cold','trimf',[0 0 40]);
fis = addmf(fis,'input',1,'warm','trimf',[30 50 70]);
fis = addmf(fis,'input',1,'hot','trimf',[60 100 100]);

% add output
fis = addvar(fis,'output','fan',[0 100]);
fis = addmf(fis,'output',1,'low','trimf',[0 0 40]);
fis = addmf(fis,'output',1,'med','trimf',[30 50 70]);
fis = addmf(fis,'output',1,'high','trimf',[60 100 100]);

% add rules: [in1mf in2mf ... outmf weight operator]
rules = [ 3 1 1 1 1;  % IF temp is hot THEN fan is high
          2 1 2 1 1;  % IF temp is warm THEN fan is med
          1 1 1 1 1]; % IF temp is cold THEN fan is low
fis = addrule(fis,rules);

% simulate & defuzzify
temp_val = 68;
out = evalfis(temp_val, fis);    % returns defuzzified crisp output
disp(['Crisp output (fan) = ', num2str(out)])

% plot
figure; plotfis(fis);
figure; ruleview(fis);


What to show in lab:

Screen of FIS editor with MFs.

Rule viewer showing firing levels and crisp output.

Surface viewer (2D/3D) if you have 2 inputs.

Print evalfis result and mention defuzzification method.


#OPTION B — Python / Colab (scikit-fuzzy) — you can run in Colab if MATLAB isn’t available
Install

In Colab first cell:

!pip install -q scikit-fuzzy

Short, exam-ready Python code (Mamdani using skfuzzy.control)
import numpy as np
import skfuzzy as fuzz
from skfuzzy import control as ctrl
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# 1. Define fuzzy variables (universe)
temp = ctrl.Antecedent(np.arange(0, 101, 1), 'temp')
cover = ctrl.Antecedent(np.arange(0, 101, 1), 'cover')   # example second input
speed = ctrl.Consequent(np.arange(0, 101, 1), 'speed')

# 2. Membership functions (triangular)
temp['cool'] = fuzz.trimf(temp.universe, [0, 0, 50])
temp['warm'] = fuzz.trimf(temp.universe, [25, 50, 75])
temp['hot']  = fuzz.trimf(temp.universe, [50, 75, 100])
cover['sunny'] = fuzz.trimf(cover.universe, [0, 0, 50])
cover['cloudy']= fuzz.trimf(cover.universe, [25,50,75])
speed['slow'] = fuzz.trimf(speed.universe, [0, 0, 50])
speed['fast'] = fuzz.trimf(speed.universe, [50, 100, 100])

# 3. Rules
rule1 = ctrl.Rule(temp['hot'] & cover['sunny'], speed['fast'])
rule2 = ctrl.Rule(temp['cool'], speed['slow'])

# 4. Control system
system = ctrl.ControlSystem([rule1, rule2])
sim = ctrl.ControlSystemSimulation(system)

# 5. Input and compute
sim.input['temp'] = 68
sim.input['cover'] = 30
sim.compute()
print("Crisp output (speed) =", sim.output['speed'])

# 6. Plots (optional)
temp.view()
speed.view()
plt.show()


#What to show in lab:

Printout of sim.output['speed'] (the crisp value).

Plots of input MFs and output MFs (temp.view() / speed.view()).

Optional: rule firing graph via rule.view() or show controlsystemsimulation result.
